{"author":{"id":"a1ea83892e62ddf2114983880dd811fc8f472fda4507e17dd770341820e892f1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1708422845,"nonce":"sL9S7P9VLJMkcIhbEUZLYrVV3kk=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s5_ypCF","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5783","origin":"github"},"title":"Improve/Fix slices in Table Compute","message":"Table Compute slices like this: 2:-2 specifies 2,1,0,-1,-2; \nthis makes no sense at all, why would one want to slice the first 3 columns and then the last two, the usual application of slice would be to select all from the second to the second last column.\nThe correct logic is implemented in `toolshed.g2.bx.psu.edu/repos/iuc/filter_tabular/filter_tabular/3.3.0`\n```\nPython offset indexes or slices. Examples:\nColumn offset indexes: 0,3,1 (selects the first,fourth, and second columns)\nNegative column numbers: -1,-2 (selects the last, and second last columns)\npython slices ( slice(start, stop[, step]) select a range of columns):\n0:3 or :3 (selects the first 3 columns)\n3:5 (selects the fourth and fifth columns)\n2: (selects all columns after the second)\n-2: (selects the last 2 columns)\n2::-1 (selects the first 3 columns n reverse order: third,second,first)\n```\n\nTo fix it one needs to look into \nhttps://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/2af4dcd9b3cea71fdae6b3aafd31079f8135a205/tools/table_compute/scripts/table_compute.py#L135-L156\n\nMaybe the `rangemaker` can just be removed, and the slices passed to pandas `iloc` as it, will investigate ...","files":null}]}